a chronology of Nietzsche's life and work, a glossary of key terms, an index of names and subjects and a guide to further readingRobert Guay provides the interpretive and philosophical context to help new readers of Nietzsche understand both On the Genealogy of Morality and Nietzsche's thought more widely. He shows how Nietzsche’s narratives engage with philosophical issues about agency, self-knowledge, historical explanation and the critique of morality.On the Genealogy of Morality has become the most common point of entry into Nietzsche’s thought. It offers relatively straightforward, sustained explanatory narratives addressing many of the main ideas of Nietzsche’s mature thought, such as will to power, nihilism, perspectivism, the value of truth and the critique of morality. At the same time, it is challenging to understand because Nietzsche intended it as an expansion and elaboration of his existing ideas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311078039040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147443079140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474430791423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474430791/original  a978-3-11-078039-0  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK